{"type":"message","id":"a4683df6","parentId":"0e0d1408","timestamp":"2026-04-13T12:25:43.149Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see another critical issue. The `novel-desktop-app/src/main/main.ts` has its OWN `projectRootPath` variable at line 10 (local to that module). But it also uses `getProjectRoot()` function at line 324. Let me check where `getProjectRoot` is defined and if it refers to the same `projectRootPath`.\n\nActually looking at the grep output:\n- Line 10: `let projectRootPath: string | null = null` (in main.ts)\n- Line 81: `export function getProjectRoot(): string | null` (probably in main.ts)\n\n\n- Line 147: `setProjectRoot(selectedPath)` (probably in main.ts)\n- Line 324: `const projectRoot = getProjectRoot()` (within an IPC handler in main.ts)\n\nSo `getProjectRoot()` is defined in `main.ts` and returns the local `projectRootPath`. But I need to check if there's a module-level `projectRootPath` in `index.ts` as well, since the grep results show both locations are referencing this same variable through different function calls.\n\nLooking at `index.ts`, it has its own `let projectRootPath: string | null = null` at the module level and exports `setProjectRoot` and `getProjectRoot` functions. However, `main.ts` uses dynamic imports for the IPC handlers, so even though both files define their own versions of these functions, they're actually using their own local copies through the dynamic import system. When IPC handlers are set up dynamically in `main.ts`, they call `getProjectRoot()` from within the same module context, so the state stays consistent within that scope. The actual architecture issue is that `main.ts` handles everything with dynamic imports, while `index.ts` is just a thin wrapper that exports `startApp` but creates its own separate state. This means there are two completely independent module systems running instead of one unified system. Now I need to check whether the preload path is ac