{"type":"message","id":"b98dcaec","parentId":"249126ad","timestamp":"2026-04-13T12:26:32.406Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the main process only uses:- `electron` - should be in devDependencies- `fs`, `path` - Node.js built-ins- `vitest` - should be in devDependencies\n- `./aiService`, `./backupService` - local modules\n\nSo the main process dependencies are fine. The `electron-store` is imported dynamically in main.ts via `await import('electron-store')`, and it's listed in the root's package.json as a dependency. But is it in `novel-desktop-app/package.json`? Let me check.\n\nActually I checked earlier - `novel-desktop-app/package.json` does NOT have `electron-store`. But the root `package.json` (not the one in `novel-desktop-app/`) does have it in dependencies. \n\nWait, I need to be more careful here. The `electron-store` import is dynamic, so it won't be caught by static analysis, but the code will definitely fail at runtime if the package isn't installed. Let me verify what's actually in `novel-desktop-app/package.json` versus the root directory.\n\nLooking at the root `package.json`, it has `electron-store@^11.0.2` in dependencies, but `novel-desktop-app/package.json` only lists `antd`, `axios`, `echarts`, `js-yaml`, `monaco-editor`, `react`, `react-dom`, and `zustand`. So `electron-store` is missing from the nested app's dependencies entirely.\n\nI also need to check if `graphology` is there—it was mentioned in the earlier analysis as being used for graph metrics, but it's not in the dependencies either.\n\nLet me trace through the actual imports: `graphology` appears to be used in `CharacterManager.tsx` based on the earlier file listing, but I don't see it in either package.json. And `vectra` which appeared in the root package.json also seems to be missing from the novel-desktop-app dependencies.","thinkingSignature":"82760ce2bc728f791aca9a758e1b5069fc11790aee9d7219f172ce3b999941e6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"c