{"type":"message","id":"e5c15806","parentId":"04317d18","timestamp":"2026-04-13T13:33:51.174Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"main.js doesn't import index.js directly. But looking at the compiled output structure, both main.js and index.js exist in dist/main/src/main/. \n\nThe problem is: the package.json says `\"main\": \"dist/main/src/main/main.js\"`. But both main.js and index.js register `fs:writeFile`. When Electron starts, it should only load main.js. But if there's some module resolution issue that also loads index.js...\n\nWait, actually - the error says \"App threw an error during load\" which means the error happens during the require/load phase of main.js. Since both files are in the same directory and both get compiled, maybe there's a module that both requires? No that doesn't make sense.\n \nLooking more carefully at the actual error - it's being thrown by the IPC handler registration itself. The package.json entry point is main.js, so when Electron starts it should only be loading that file. Unless index.js is somehow being pulled in as a dependency of main.js, but the compiled output doesn't show any require statements pointing to it. The fact that both files are being compiled to the same output directory suggests they might be getting executed separately somehow. Both files are legitimate entry points with `fs:writeFile` handlers, and since the package.json only specifies `main.js` as the entry point, `index.js` shouldn't be loaded at all. The compilation is outputting both files to the same directory, but there's no import statement linking them, so they should remain independent. I need to look more carefully at what's actually in index.js to understand why both handlers might be firing.","thinkingSignature":"688c9ee673e33139fa9fb8f08c73d4226a268f4634b7a1af61749f1abde84908"},{"type":"text","text":"两个文件都独立注册了这个 handler，但 package.json 只指向 main.js。检查 index.js 是否被间接加载：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_functio