e Sider is properly contained within the layout hierarchy.\n\nThe outer Layout contains a Header and a nested Layout with three children: the icon Sider (64px), the content Sider (300px), and the Content. The right Sider (360px) is actually outside this nested Layout, which could be causing a structural problem. I should check if removing that right Sider from its current position and placing it inside the nested Layout alongside the other two Siders would fix the rendering. The right Sider at the same level as the nested Layout might be causing rendering issues. I should ask the user to open DevTools and inspect the actual DOM structure to see what's happening, or check if there are any JavaScript errors preventing the right side from rendering at all. Let me also verify whether there's a CSS or layout issue specific to how Ant Design's Layout and Sider components interact when nested at different levels. I should look at the actual IntegratedWorkbench code to see if there's something obviously wrong, but I'm realizing the real issue might be that the user upgraded esbuild but the build is still using cached modules. When I ran `npm start` on Windows, it triggered `prestart` which runs the full build process, so it should have picked up the changes, but there might be a caching issue preventing the new code from taking effect.\n\nThe console shows the mock electron API is active, which means the app is running in a dev or test mode rather than with the actual Electron API. But IntegratedWorkbench imports from stores that use window.electronAPI, so if that's not properly set up, it could cause rendering issues. Let me step back and think about what's actually preventing the right side from displaying—it's either a JavaScript error I haven't spotted, a layout problem with the Sider, or something specific to how the component is structured.\n\nLooking at the render condition, it checks `currentFile ? ... : ...`. Since no chapter is selected yet, `currentFile` should be null, which means it should render the placeholder. But if the placeholder isn't showing either, then either `currentFile` isn't actually null or there's something wrong with how the component is being rendered at all. Let me check if the placeholder has the correct styling and structure to actually appear on screen.\n\nThe placeholder uses flexbox with centered content, but if the parent Content div has `minHeight: 0` and no actual height, the flex centering won't work. I need to check if the Content div is actually receiving a proper height value.\n\nLooking at the layout structure: the outer Layout has `height: '100vh'`, and the inner Content doesn't have an explicit height set, so it's relying on the flexbox layout to fill the remaining space. With `flex: 1` and `minHeight: 0`, it should expand to fill available space, but I'm not certain the Content is actually getting any height at all. The real issue might be that the Content div has no height because its children (the MarkdownEditor or placeholder) aren't rendering with proper dimensions, so I should check if that's what's causing the blank right side. I'm realizing the placeholder might not even be rendering if `currentFile` isn't null—I should add some debugging to check what's actually happening. Let me reconsider the overall layout structure: I have a 64px icon Sider on the left, then a nested Layout containing a 300px content Sider and the main Content area, with the 360px right Sider floating outside. This nesting might be causing the rendering issue.\n\nActually, I think the problem is that the right Sider is a separate component outside the nested Layout rather than being inside it with the other two Siders. Let me restructure this so the icon Sider, content Sider, Content, and right Sider are all siblings in the same Layout, which is the correct Ant Design pattern. I'll move the right Sider inside the nested Layout where it belongs.","thinkingSignature":"5b437820cf25f4f60128e7e733b96770ab146fd1eae