{"type":"message","id":"e8fd27b9","parentId":"6ac7f428","timestamp":"2026-04-13T13:46:09.416Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the issue now. The Layout structure is:\n\n```\n<Layout>  // outer\n  <Header />\n  <Layout>  // inner\n    <Sider width={64} />  // icon menu\n    <Sider width={300} />  // left content\n    <Content />  // center\n    <Sider width={360} />  // right AI tools\n  </Layout>\n</Layout>\n```\n\nThe outer Layout has:\n- Header\n- Layout (inner)\n\nThe inner Layout has:\n- Sider (64px, icon menu)\n- Sider (300px, left content)\n- Content (center)\n\n\n- Sider (360px, right AI tools)\n\nThis looks correct to me - the right Sider is a sibling of Content within the inner Layout. But I'm realizing the real problem might be that the outer Layout itself doesn't have `height: '100vh'` set, so even though the inner Layout is flexed, there's no explicit height on the root Layout to constrain it.\n\nActually, looking at the styles again, the outer Layout does have `height: '100vh'` and the inner Layout should stretch to fill that space with `flex: 1`. But the user's description of the right side being \"completely blank\" suggests the Content area is taking up all the available space, which makes me wonder if the right Sider is actually rendering but just invisible somehow. I should verify whether it's a rendering issue or a visibility issue.\n\nLet me reconsider the Layout structure itself. In Ant Design 4's Layout system, the Sider component should respond to window resizing and content changes, but if the right Sider is positioned as a sibling rather than nested properly within the Content area, it might not be getting the right layout context. I need to restructure this so the Sider is a sibling of Content, not wrapped inside it.\n\nLooking at the current structure, the Sider with width={360} is positioned outside the nested Content Sider, which is correct. But I should verify that the flex layout is set up