{"type":"message","id":"8eb56567","parentId":"8b5a8f28","timestamp":"2026-04-13T14:33:58.824Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user says there's no change at all. Let me think about this carefully.\n\nThe core problem is:\n1. WSL and Windows share the same D:\\ files\n2. I update files in WSL, they should be visible to Windows\n3. But npm start rebuilds from source, and the Windows esbuild version was stale\n\nThe user ran `npm install esbuild@latest --save-dev` and then `npm start`, but there's still no change.\n\nWait - actually, let me reconsider. The npm start command runs `prestart` which runs `build:all` which runs `build:main` and then `vite build`. \n\nWhen vite builds, it reads the source files from the D: drive. Since WSL and Windows share the same filesystem, the source files I'm writing to in WSL should be visible to Windows. So the real issue might be that the component itself isn't actually changing the layout behavior - the old version had nested Layout/Sider components while the new one uses plain flexbox divs, but maybe the build isn't picking up these changes or there's something else preventing the new code from taking effect. I should probably check what the current state of the file actually looks like in the Windows build output.\n\nWait, I'm realizing the user reported \"no change at all\" after I asked them to reinstall esbuild and run npm start. If they ran those commands, the build should have completed and launched Electron. So if there's still no visible change, it could mean the old component is still being loaded from cache, or maybe the issue is that WSL and Windows are writing to different locations despite appearing to share the same D:\\ path - WSL might be writing to /mnt/d/ which maps differently than the actual Windows D:\\ drive.\n\nActually, thinking about this more carefully: when npm start runs on Windows, it's executing in Windows with its own node_modules and build environment. Th