{"type":"message","id":"22fb4579","parentId":"8ccbd09f","timestamp":"2026-04-13T14:44:58.285Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me try a cleaner approach - use `cmd.exe /c start` to launch the electron app as a separate Windows process, detached from the WSL session. Actually, let me just tell the user the situation - I've built successfully, the files are on D:\\ which is the same as /mnt/d/, so the user can run `npm start` on Windows and it should pick up the new build.\n\nBut the issue is that Windows npm start has the prestart hook which runs build:all, and that uses the Windows node_modules. The Windows node_modules has the OLD (broken) esbuild, unless the user already ran `npm install esbuild@latest --save-dev` on Windows.\n\n\nI could try invoking the Windows npx command directly from WSL to bypass the prestart hook entirely, which might avoid the esbuild issue on Windows.","thinkingSignature":"16ac8bd01f88e45bdd5eddeb5110dd4d57d3da5d820618a844167568eef69fb9"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_g27ydf2f51z7_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"/mnt/c/Windows/System32/cmd.exe /c \"cd /d D:\\aafuzhi\\axs\\novel-desktop-app && npm install esbuild@latest --save-dev && npx electron .\" 2>&1 &\nsleep 3\necho \"Electron launch attempted\"","timeout":15}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":62893,"output":268,"cacheRead":19262,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":82423,"cost":{"input":0.0188679,"output":0.0003216,"cacheRead":0.0011557199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.020345219999999997}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776091489568,"responseId":"062c34602f7e4d6bc6e2779095242b81"}}
