{"type":"message","id":"337414e3","parentId":"955991e5","timestamp":"2026-04-13T14:48:51.289Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CSS in `index-999e7368.css` (which is what `index.html` references) DOES have `display:flex;flex-direction:column` for `.content-panel`:\n\n```css\n.content-panel{border-radius:8px;height:calc(100vh - 120px);overflow:hidden;box-shadow:0 1px 4px #0000000f;display:flex;flex-direction:column}\n```\n\nSo the CSS fix IS in the right file!\n\nAnd the JS chunk `index-4ce7a73b.js` (referenced by index.html) DOES contain \"创作工作台\".\n \nBoth assets are definitely in the build output. The issue might be that Electron is loading cached versions of these files instead of the fresh ones. I could try clearing the Electron cache programmatically, but first I need to understand what URL the BrowserWindow is actually loading from.\n\nLooking at the flow: when `npm start` runs `electron .`, it loads from `app.getAppPath()`, which should be the project root where we built the files. So the new build should be picked up automatically.\n\nI'm wondering if the real culprit is vite's module caching in the renderer process, especially with lazy imports like `const ChapterWorkspace = React.lazy(() => import('./components/ChapterWorkspace'))`. Even if we replaced the source file with `IntegratedWorkbench`, vite might still be caching the old module somewhere.\n\nBut wait - I actually deleted `ChapterWorkspace.tsx`, so if the old code was still running, it would crash trying to load that missing module. Yet the user reported no change, not a missing module error. And when I grepped through the built JS files, I found \"创作工作台\" in `index-4ce7a73b.js`, which suggests the new file was actually built. So the new code is there, but maybe it's not actually being executed.\n\nLet me think through this differently - when I modified `App.tsx` to import `IntegratedWorkbench` instead of `ChapterWorkspace`, I updated the import statement