{"type":"message","id":"897ab18b","parentId":"02aed380","timestamp":"2026-04-13T14:55:42.535Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, the bundle contains the title text \"🍅 创作工作台\" 3 times. This confirms the IntegratedWorkbench component IS in the bundle with the correct content.\n\nNow let me check if there's something wrong with how the app loads. Let me check if maybe the `workspace` case in App.tsx is not being reached.\n\nActually, let me look at the App.tsx workspace case more carefully:\n```jsx\ncase 'workspace':\n  return (\n    <div className=\"content-panel\" style={{ background: colorBgContainer, height: 'calc(100vh - 120px)', overflow: 'hidden' }}>\n\n\n```\n\nWait, I'm seeing a mismatch here. The App.tsx is applying inline styles directly to the content-panel div, but I also added `.content-panel` class styles in App.css with `display: flex` and `flex-direction: column`. The inline styles don't include `display: flex`, so there's a conflict between what the class is supposed to do and what's being applied inline.\n\nActually, looking at the App.css again, the `.content-panel` class does have `display: flex` and `flex-direction: column` with `height: calc(100vh - 120px)`. Since both the class and inline styles are being applied, the inline `height` and `overflow: hidden` would override the class rules, but `display: flex` from the class should still take effect since it's not being overridden inline.\n\nSo the class should win for `display: flex`. But the user is saying the layout isn't working. Let me check if maybe the class simply isn't being applied at all, or if there's something else preventing the flex behavior from working as expected.\n\nWait, could this actually be an Electron caching problem? The user deleted the dist folder, so that shouldn't be the issue unless Electron itself is caching the rendered output. But another possibility is that the user's build failed silently. When they ran `npm start` after deleting dist, the prestart script ran `npm run build:all`, but if the TypeScript compilation failed in the main process, the entire build would have stopped without generating the dist folder properly.\n\nActually, looking back at the conversation history, I can see the Windows build DID succeed - it showed the success message and the file count. But then the user deleted the dist folder afterward and ran npm start again. The real issue is probably that npm start is caching the build output from before the dist folder was deleted.\n\nWhen the user ran npm start with the deleted dist folder, the prestart hook should have triggered a fresh build, but it might have used cached results instead. The build DID succeed and created the index.html with the correct script references, so the real problem is likely that the old cached build is being served while the new changes aren't taking effect.\n\nLet me look at the actual build errors to see what went wrong.","thinkingSignature":"101f855d84dec21ad8942aa7ee7bab2a8bc2d1b1da0709a07c38e8d907c4a667"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_1bk9zc89bdna_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /mnt/d/aafuzhi/axs/novel-desktop-app/dist/renderer/assets/index-4ce7a73b.js && echo \"---\" && date"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":79839,"output":649,"cacheRead":19262,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":99750,"cost":{"input":0.0239517,"output":0.0007788,"cacheRead":0.0011557199999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.025886219999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776092123112,"responseId":"062c36db5df095c733ea251a029e5d9a"}}
