{"type":"message","id":"b958e92c","parentId":"fbd04bc6","timestamp":"2026-04-13T15:21:15.165Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so `openFile` just stores the path as-is. When CharacterManager calls `openFile('characters/name.yaml', '')` with a relative path, the store will have `currentFile.path = 'characters/name.yaml'`.\n\nBut then later when the MarkdownEditor or YAMLEditor tries to save or display content, it might use `currentFile.path` with relative path which could fail.But actually this is an EXISTING issue in the ChapterWorkspace too - the CharacterManager in the original code also did:```tsx<CharacterManager onSelectFile={(path) => {  openFile(path, '')} />}```\n\nSo this is a pre-existing issue, not something I introduced. The proper fix would be to use `joinPath(projectRoot, path)` when calling `openFile`. But let me focus on what's NEW vs EXISTING.For now, let me note this as a pre-existing issue and focus on the INTEGRATION WORKBENCH specific problems.\n\n\nI've identified the real issues: the `openFile` call in IntegratedWorkbench's CharacterManager tab uses a relative path when it should be absolute, and OutlineTree had a Vite production build problem with Node.js `path.join` that I've already fixed by switching to `joinPath`. The main.ts loadFile path looks correct with the three-level traversal.\n\nThe App.css .content-panel has flex and column-direction set properly, and App.tsx is using IntegratedWorkbench instead of ChapterWorkspace. I should note that the relative path issue in CharacterManager is pre-existing, but I could fix it by wrapping the path with `joinPath` when calling `openFile`.","thinkingSignature":"a717b1ced861f64dd3f128344af2ccd13d911aca74c4f3f8829c79e48b8d38de"},{"type":"text","text":"发现问题！CharacterManager 的 `onSelectFile` 用相对路径，会导致 `currentFile.path` 是相对路径而崩溃。修掉：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3ogcd7z8jvn5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n \"openFile.*onSelect